m archives in four countries, Anderson explores Britain’s role in Egypt during this period and how the ELC came to be, as well as the experiences and hardships these men endured. As he examines the ways they coped—through music, theater, drugs, religion, strikes, and mutiny—he illustrates how Egyptian nationalists, seeing their countrymen in a state akin to slavery, began to grasp that they had been racialized as “people of color.” Documenting the history of the ELC and its work during the First World War, The Egyptian Labor Corps also provides a fascinating reinterpretation of the 1919 revolution through the lens of critical race theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aEgyptiansxRace identityxHistory. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xCampaignszEgyptzSinai. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xCampaignszPalestine. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xConscript laborxSocial aspectszEgypt. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aEgyptian history, First World War, 1919 Egyptian Revolution, British Empire, Egypt, modern Egypt, Modern middle east, anti-Blackness, race in Egypt, race in the middle east.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477324554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477324554/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK